    thinking: "**Designing the `index.html`**\n\nI\'m starting to visualize the `index.html` design. The current focus is the `<style>` section. I\'m planning a responsive CSS template. Key elements will be: Google Fonts imports for Orbitron (headings), Inter (body text), and JetBrains Mono (coding data). I\'m also planning the particle canvas system to be embedded.\n\n\n**Refining the CSS Framework**\n\nI\'m now deep-diving into the CSS specifics. I\'m focusing on crafting reusable classes like `.neon-border-blue` and `.card` to define visual styles. I\'m keen on custom scrollbars and a responsive grid layout. I\'m also planning animations: pulse, glow, typing, and float effects. My layout vision incorporates 12 columns for desktop, stacking into a single column for smaller devices.\n\n\n\n**Synthesizing Audio Elements**\n\nI\'m now figuring out the audio implementation. It begins with lazy initialization of the `AudioContext` to comply with autoplay restrictions. I will develop functions for various sound effects: success (C-major arpeggio), error (low buzz), level-up (pitch sweep with chime), and click (high-pass click), all utilizing oscillators. I\'m prioritizing clean, browser-compliant audio playback.\n\n**Structuring the Game Arena**\n\nNow, I\'m defining the game area overlay using a dynamic modal. I\'ll use the `#game-arena-overlay` container with an `#game-arena-body`. On card clicks, `openGame(gameId)` triggers loading custom HTML and a game-specific startup function inside the body. This setup supports a dynamic and modular game selection process.\n\n\n**Designing Game-Specific Arenas**\n\nI\'m working on the architecture for game-specific arenas now. Each game will get its own HTML canvas and game logic. I\'m focusing on \"Neuron Builder\" right now; it\'ll have input, hidden, and output layers, each with different node configurations. I\'m planning particle effects to bring the network connections alive, with glowing lines and traveling electrical particles! My goal is to craft a visually captivating and interactive experience.\n\n\n**Implementing Node Connections**\n\nI\'m now implementing the node connection system! I\'ve added click-to-drag functionality for nodes and real-time line drawing from the source node to the mouse. I\'ll connect nodes with a click and release over a valid target, storing this in a \'connections\' array and triggering a sound and visual electrical burst effect on connect. I\'m also now implementing connection rules for hidden and output nodes, along with a `Network Strength` calculation based on layer coverage, and planning the \"Boss Challenge Dialogue\" sequence.\n\n\n**Defining New Game Concepts**\n\nI\'m now designing two additional games. \"Data Sorter\" will employ an image carousel for player interaction, featuring an emoji and description card with timed responses. It features progressive difficulty levels from clean data to noisy/corrupt data that needs the \"SKIP/DATA KOTOR\" button. A dynamic accuracy chart keeps track. I\'m also planning \"Prompt Wizard\" as a third game.\n\n\n**Crafting the Desk Interface**\n\nI\'m now designing the magical desk interface with a distinct inventory and spell book layout. I\'m visualizing the left side for \"Inventory / Spell Ingredients,\" categorizing prompt blocks by Role, Task, Format, and Constraint, each with a unique color. The center will house the \"Spell Book / Prompt Slot Columns,\" a grid of slots to hold the blocks. I am also working on dynamic visual feedback for the user.\n\n\n\n**Conceptualizing Game 4**\n\nI\'m now outlining a new game, \"Model Showdown\"! It\'s a fighting game layout with two zones: a \"Client Request\" in the center and three glowing character cards representing model heroes: Classification (cyber assassin), Regression (wizard), and Clustering (golem). The game presents five cases; the player selects the correct hero card for each, triggering attack animations if correct. A streak bonus of massive confetti will be the reward for five correct answers!\n\n\n**Designing Overfitting Escape**\n\nI\'m now deep into designing \"Overfitting Escape,\" a retro labyrinth game. I\'m focusing on the canvas layout for this classic 2D game. I\'m especially focused on the Model Complexity Slider, which has values from 1 to 10. The AI path redraws in real-time as the slider moves, creating different behaviors: low values lead to underfitting with AIKO yelling \"Model terlalu malas untuk belajar pola,\" while high values result in overfitting.\n\n\n**Finalizing Verdicts**\n\nI\'m now implementing the \"Ethical AI Judge\" game. I\'ve designed a courtroom scene and a virtual scales of justice. Now I\'m focused on the case presentation and verdict choices. I\'m prioritizing clear case descriptions and intuitive verdict options: \"Approve,\" \"Flag,\" and \"Reject.\" The goal is for players to engage with ethical considerations in AI deployment. I\'ll need to define the implications of each verdict on the balance of fairness and profit!\n\n\n**Finalizing Verdicts**\n\nI\'m now implementing the \"Ethical AI Judge\" game. I\'ve designed a courtroom scene and a virtual scales of justice. Now I\'m focused on the case presentation and verdict choices. I\'m prioritizing clear case descriptions and intuitive verdict options: \"Approve,\" \"Flag,\" and \"Reject.\" The goal is for players to engage with ethical considerations in AI deployment. I\'ll need to define the implications of each verdict on the balance of fairness and profit! I am now focused on a conversational dialog from Aiko that gives feedback after each selection. Completing the hearings rewards XP and locks the \"Ethical Thinker\" badge. I am now focused on including a custom sound oscillation and a CSS particle background. Finally, I will build an interactive AI Conversational Desk for Aiko.\n\n\n"
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_MAX_TOKENS
  }
