    thinking: "**Refining the Exclusion Criteria**\n\nI\'ve realized the initial exclusion strategy was too broad. The directory search was still including files like `package-lock.json`, which contributed significantly to the failure. This necessitated a refinement of the exclusion criteria to encompass specific file types or a more targeted exclusion pattern. I\'m focusing on the types and locations of files that are known to be problematic during searches.\n\n\n**Investigating Fetch Behavior**\n\nI\'m now diving into the `fetch` issue. My key focus has narrowed to how `formdata-polyfill` interacts with `fetch` in the browser environment. I\'m exploring the problem of a read-only `globalThis.fetch` on iframes and virtual container sandboxes, which leads to the error. Now, I\'m thinking of ways to patch the `fetch` getter/setter behavior so that the error doesn\'t throw. I\'ve realized I can redefine `window.fetch` to be configurable and writable, or define a writable property on `globalThis` or `window`! My focus has evolved: intercepting it before execution is key.\n\n\n**Implementing the `fetch` Fix**\n\nI\'ve hit upon a robust solution! I can redefine `window.fetch` and `globalThis.fetch` as configurable and writable right at the application\'s outset, specifically in `src/main.tsx`. This addresses the read-only issue in sandboxed environments directly. Using `Object.defineProperty` provides a standard and reliable means to make the property modifiable. I\'ve realized it\'s a straightforward strategy, making fetch writable, ensuring the property\'s descriptor will be correctly set.\n\n\n**Analyzing Property Attributes**\n\nI\'m now investigating the specific attributes of the `fetch` property on `window`. My concern is whether it\'s currently non-configurable; if so, redefining it with `Object.defineProperty` might throw an error. However, standard browser behavior suggests `window.fetch` is generally configurable. The goal is to confirm this before implementing any changes.\n\n\n**Confirming the Patching Approach**\n\nI\'ve determined a safe and efficient strategy for this `fetch` issue. I\'ll wrap the `Object.defineProperty` attempts in `try-catch` blocks, which prevents the application from crashing. I can check if the issue is rooted in `Window.prototype` and adjust accordingly. It seems like the approach is successful: If I redefine `window.fetch` to be writable, libraries like `global.fetch = ...` will then work perfectly. I believe this solves the root of the problem!\n\n\n**Confirming Placement Strategy**\n\nI\'ve confirmed the strategic placement for patching `fetch`. Ensuring the patch runs *before* any other script touches `fetch` is paramount. The entry point, `/src/main.tsx`, is the ideal location. I\'ve examined `/src/main.tsx` again and verified that the code should be placed at the beginning of the file to ensure the patch executes first. This is because no imports are processed until after the root is created.\n\n\n**Refining the Patch Logic**\n\nI\'m now refining the fallback strategy for the `fetch` patch. I\'ll implement a tiered approach, attempting `Object.defineProperty` on `window`, then `globalThis`, and finally, the `Window.prototype`. The `try-catch` blocks will handle any failures. If the `window` level patch fails, I\'ll attempt a `Window.prototype` level patch. This ensures maximum compatibility across different environments. I have now written out the code!\n\n\n\n"
